     <title>2014 GEICO Associate Degree Scholars Receive $2,000 in Scholarships</title> 
     <link>https://www.ptk.org/news/GEICO%20Associate%20Degree%20Scholars%20Announced 
     <description>
      &lt;div class="field field-name-field-dateline field-type-datestamp field-label-hidden"&gt;&lt;div class="field-items"&gt;&lt;div class="field-item even"&gt;&lt;span class="date-display-single" property="dc:date" datatype="xsd:dateTime" content="2014-10-08T00:00:00-05:00"&gt;Wednesday, October 8, 2014&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden"&gt;&lt;div class="field-items"&gt;&lt;div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Jackson, MS &amp;ndash; As the son of a single parent, Brandon Hayes set five goals for himself to break the stereotypes commonly associated with single parent families &amp;ndash; achieve academic excellence; maintain a good reputation through strong moral values; give back to his community through volunteerism; build a successful career in business and establish college scholarships for single-parent students. Now he is well on his way to achieving those goals as one of two 2014 recipients of Phi Theta Kappa&amp;rsquo;s $1,000 GEICO Pathway to Completion Associate Degree Scholarships.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div class="caption_photo right"&gt;&lt;a class="colorbox colorbox-insert-image" href="https://www.ptk.org/sites/default/files/brandon%20hayes%207492%20%282%29.jpg" rel="gallery-all" title=""&gt;&lt;img alt="" src="https://www.ptk.org/sites/default/files/styles/medium/public/brandon%20hayes%207492%20%282%29.jpg?itok=9wvRNGiE" title="" typeof="foaf:Image" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;p&gt;Brandon Hayes&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="caption_photo right"&gt;&lt;a class="colorbox colorbox-insert-image" href="https://www.ptk.org/sites/default/files/emilie%20st-pierre.jpg" rel="gallery-all" title=""&gt;&lt;img alt="" src="https://www.ptk.org/sites/default/files/styles/medium/public/emilie%20st-pierre.jpg?itok=jHkCnHrv" title="" typeof="foaf:Image" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;p&gt;Emilie St. Pierre&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Employed with Chick-Fil-A since he was 14, Hayes entered their leadership internship program in his first year of employment and was the youngest employee to fulfill a management leadership position in his area. He graduated from high school as a Tennessee Scholar with highest honors, volunteered 150 hours at a local hospital, and entered Walters State Community College, where he maintains a 4.0 grade point average.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Hayes holds leadership positions with the college&amp;rsquo;s Student Government Association and his Phi Theta Kappa chapter, and he serves as a Senate Page. He hopes to transfer to East Tennessee State University to double major in accounting and finance and pursue master&amp;#39;s and doctoral degrees in economics and business at the University of Tennessee-Knoxville. Hayes hopes to own and operate a Chick-Fil-A franchise, mentor high school and college students and give back to the community by developing a college scholarship program to help other children of single parents.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The second 2014 GEICO Scholar is Emilie St. Pierre. Taking her first programming class at the College of Southern Nevada challenged her and cultivated an interest in networking forensics. While maintaining a 3.91 grade point average, St. Pierre serves as Math Club President and as a PC and server repair technician within her community.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;A member of Phi Theta Kappa, she is pursuing an Associate of Arts degree in Network Security and Computer Forensics. St. Pierre plans to pursue a career in cybersecurity, helping organizations investigate their data structure and past breaches to implement strategies to avoid future work disruption.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The GEICO Pathway to Completion Associate Degree Scholarships are presented by GEICO to Phi Theta Kappa members pursuing associate degrees. A sponsor of the Phi Theta Kappa Annual Convention, GEICO has given more than $1 million to support scholarships and programs for Phi Theta Kappa members. GEICO also provides additional scholarships to Phi Theta Kappa members for the completion of baccalaureate and master&amp;rsquo;s degrees and for the professional development for chapter advisors.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;These scholarships of $1,000 each are given to Phi Theta Kappa members who have held a significant leadership position on campus or in their community, with preference given to those who have held chapter, regional or international office. Phi Theta Kappa provides more than 900 applicants worldwide in excess of $230,000 in scholarships to complete associate level studies each fall.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;GEICO is a member of the Berkshire Hathaway family of companies and is the third-largest private passenger auto insurance company in the United States, serving more than 12 million private passenger customers and insuring more than 18 million vehicles (auto and cycle).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Phi Theta Kappa Honor Society, headquartered in Jackson, Mississippi, is the largest honor society in higher education with 1,285 chapters on college campuses in all 50 of the United States, plus Canada, Germany, the Republic of Palau, Peru, the Republic of the Marshall Islands, the Federated States of Micronesia, the British Virgin Islands, the United Arab Emirates and U.S. territorial possessions. Nearly 3 million students have been inducted since its founding in 1918, with approximately 131,000 students inducted annually.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="field field-name-field-article-tags field-type-taxonomy-term-reference field-label-inline clearfix"&gt;&lt;div class="field-label"&gt;Tags:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="field-items"&gt;&lt;div class="field-item even"&gt;&lt;a href="/taxonomy/term/191" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel" datatype=""&gt;Events &amp;amp; Awards&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="field-item odd"&gt;&lt;a href="/taxonomy/term/192" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel" datatype=""&gt;Press Room&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
     </description> 
