    <item> 
     <title>Jack Kent Cooke Scholarship App Opens Oct. 6; Amount Increased</title> 
     <link>https://www.ptk.org/news/jack-kent-cooke-app-opening 
     <description>
      &lt;div class="field field-name-field-dateline field-type-datestamp field-label-hidden"&gt;&lt;div class="field-items"&gt;&lt;div class="field-item even"&gt;&lt;span class="date-display-single" property="dc:date" datatype="xsd:dateTime" content="2014-10-03T00:00:00-05:00"&gt;Friday, October 3, 2014&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden"&gt;&lt;div class="field-items"&gt;&lt;div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Applications for the Jack Kent Cooke Foundation&amp;rsquo;s &lt;a href="http://www.jkcf.org/scholarship-programs/undergraduate-transfer/"&gt;2015 Undergraduate Transfer Scholarship&lt;/a&gt; &amp;mdash; the largest undergraduate scholarship in the nation &amp;mdash; will be accepted beginning October 6.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Up to 85 of the nation&amp;rsquo;s top two-year college students will be selected to receive $40,000 each per year for up to three years to complete a bachelor&amp;rsquo;s degree at an accredited college or university in the United States. The Foundation recently increased the amount awarded from $30,000.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;We believe it is important for our Scholars to graduate from college as close to debt free as possible so that they can maximize the career and graduate school opportunities that await them,&amp;rdquo; said Emily Froimson, Vice President of Programs at the Jack Kent Cooke Foundation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The deadline to apply for the scholarship is December 2.&lt;/strong&gt; A &lt;a href="http://info.jkcf.org/jkcf15-0-0-0"&gt;webinar&lt;/a&gt; for the 2015 Undergraduate Transfer Scholarship will be held October 9 at 4 pm ET. Learn more about the &lt;a href="http://www.jkcf.org/"&gt;Jack Kent Cooke Foundation.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In 2014, 71 of the 85 undergraduate transfer scholarship recipients were Phi Theta Kappa members. Among them was Lori King-Nelson, who along with her family had been struggling financially since she began attending classes as a non-traditional student at Tarrant County College&amp;rsquo;s South Campus in Texas.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;To know things are going to be okay over the next few years while I finish my degree is pretty overwhelming,&amp;rdquo; she said.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In addition to the $120,000 award each student stands to receive, the Foundation offers up to $50,000 each to scholars upon the completion of their baccalaureate degree if they meet renewal criteria and continue enrollment for a master&amp;rsquo;s degree.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I always wanted to go as high as I could go in my education; but until recently, that wasn&amp;rsquo;t a reality,&amp;rdquo; said Dennis Murphy, a 2014 Jack Kent Cooke Scholar from Middlesex Community College in Massachusetts and a Phi Theta Kappa chapter officer. &amp;ldquo;This award gives me the opportunity to achieve the education I need to reach my dreams. It&amp;rsquo;s opening doors.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;According to the Jack Kent Cooke Foundation, only about 12 percent of two-year college students who express interest in earning a bachelor&amp;rsquo;s degree actually reach that goal. Many students are deterred by the high price of four-year colleges, the limited options for transfer students and a lack of knowledge about the possible academic pathways, the foundation has found.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;This is why partnerships providing varied sources of stackable scholarships matter,&amp;rdquo; said Phi Theta Kappa Executive Director and CEO Dr. Rod Risley. &amp;ldquo;While we are extremely grateful for the commitment the Jack Kent Cooke Foundation has made to our two-year college students, more foundations and organizations must invest in our nation&amp;rsquo;s students.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s not only an investment that will benefit the students; it&amp;rsquo;s an investment that will benefit us all.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Jack Kent Cooke Scholars are selected based on high academic ability and achievements, persistence, leadership and financial need. The average GPA of the 2014 Scholars is 3.98, and they come from families with an average adjusted gross income of approximately $25,000.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;The Jack Kent Cooke Foundation has long been committed to helping outstanding community college students transfer to and succeed at the nation&amp;rsquo;s top colleges and universities,&amp;rdquo; Froimson said. &amp;ldquo;Since the program started in 2002, the Foundation has supported 643 community college students directly, and thousands more through the Foundation&amp;rsquo;s grant-making initiatives.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Past Undergraduate Transfer Scholars have attended such prestigious colleges as Amherst College, Columbia University, Cornell University, Georgetown University, Stanford University, Wellesley College and Yale University. Among the 2013 Scholars, 62 percent were first-generation college students.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;And although Phi Theta Kappa membership is not required for this award, Society members often make up a large percentage of the recipients each year.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Students who engage in Phi Theta Kappa programs gain immeasurably from the experience and are recognized for their achievements by prestigious scholarship providers like the Jack Kent Cooke Foundation,&amp;rdquo; Risley said. &amp;ldquo;Consistently, the majority of scholarship recipients are engaged Phi Theta Kappa members.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;We value the strong working relationship that Phi Theta Kappa has for many years shared with the Jack Kent Cooke Foundation in providing our members access to selective senior colleges.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="field field-name-field-article-tags field-type-taxonomy-term-reference field-label-inline clearfix"&gt;&lt;div class="field-label"&gt;Tags:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="field-items"&gt;&lt;div class="field-item even"&gt;&lt;a href="/taxonomy/term/190" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel" datatype=""&gt;Engagement&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
